We will be using E. coli NEB 10 cell as chassis to both clone and help assemble our device.  The NEB10 cells will, depending upon the stage of the work, contain plasmids that contain one or two antibiotic resistant genes (ampicillin, kanamycin, tetracycline, and or chloramphenicol) and these require our BSL-2 biosafety cabinet.

While not a virus, we will be using two plasmids that have the potential to infect and modify the genome of mammalian cells.  These plasmid are part of the Thermo Fisher "Flp In" gene expression system.  The pOG44 plasmid contains a recombinase enzyme and the capability of installing a cassette containing an expression system with a multiple cloning site to drop in a coding region using an other plasmid: pcDNA-T5-FRO which is a shuttle vector for the addition of a selected coding sequence (a calcium channel or modified calmodulin protein).  Both have the potential to be infectious, theoretically and need to be handled appropriately (BCL-2).

Finally we will be culturing a mammalian cell lines: HEP2K (human kidney), BHK-21 (hamster kidney), and CHO K1 (hamster ovary) cells.  While all of these have been provided by ATCC or Thermo Fisher and have been screened for the presence of human pathogens, they are at risk of being transiently infected during the process of handling.  We have a dedicated BSL-2, type II (external exhaust) biosafety cabinet for their handling.

Pseudomonas aeruginosa is an opportunist pathogen against humans and is the most commonly used strain in the laboratory. It is a gram negative bacterium with a DNA of about 6.3 Kbp length.

We are working on attenuated bacterial strains such as: Pseudomonas aeruginosa PAO1. Indeed, their virulence genes have been removed to make them non-pathogenic for humans. 

For our proof of concept, we are using a synthetic fragment of the bactrium's DNA. So here, the bacteria itself is not used here. 

However, we use those bacterias to show efficiency of the bacteriophages as they need to be as specific as possible to a bacterium. So, we manipulate bacteriophages which are viruses that only infect bacteria in the most specific way. 
The bacteriophages we are using are PAKP3 and HER18. PAKP3 is a specific bacteriophage against Pseudomonas aeruginosa PAK strain. HER18 is specific to Pseudomonas aeruginosa PAO1.

All our manipulations regarding biobricks will be done using the strain Escherichia coli DH5alpha and TOP10. Indeed, we are transforming them so that fluorescence is emitted and detected.

E.coli DH5alpha (K12 strain). These cells will be used to propagate our plasmids. We would like to transfer a synthetic DNA-Sequence from Plasmodium into the plasmids. We aim to use this sequence as a template as a positive control for a PCR to develop a PCR-test-system for the detection of Plasmodium.  

E.coli Xl1 blue (K12 strain). These cells will be used to propagate our plasmids as an alternative to DH5 alpha. We would like to clone synthetic subgenomic DNA-sequence from Plasmodium into the plasmids. We aim to use this sequence as a template as a positive control for a PCR to develop a PCR-test-system for the detection of Plasmodium.  These strains have been used for the Interlab Study.

We used HEK293T cells. Cells were transfected with GFP expression plasmids as a source for gfp RNA. This RNA was isolated and used to establish our test systems. 

If the vote for our safety check-in for genomic DNA of Plasmodium species is positive we would like work with non-infectios and non-toxic genomic DNA of Plasmodium. It will be provided to us from another lab who will extract the DNA from their cultured Plasmodiums (safety level 2 orgnaism: see https://www.baua.de/DE/Angebote/Rechtstexte-und-Technische-Regeln/Regelwerk/TRBA/pdf/TRBA-100.pdf?__blob=publicationFile, page 46).
